#!/bin/bash

cat <<'EOF'

Zenlog — automatic per-command shell logging.

Zenlog wraps your login shell and saves every command's output to its own log
file, tagged with metadata (directory, git branch, timestamps, etc.).

USAGE
  zenlog                           Start a new logged shell session
  zenlog SUBCOMMAND [OPTIONS]      Run a subcommand

QUICK START
  zenlog init                      Create ~/.zenlog.toml and patch your shell RC
  zenlog                           Start a logged session
  zenlog open-last-log             View the previous command's output

HOTKEYS (inside a zenlog session)
  ALT+1    Open last command output in $ZENLOG_VIEWER (default: less)
  ALT+2    Open last output in browser with color (requires a2h)
  ALT+3    Pick any recent log with fzf, open in $ZENLOG_VIEWER
  ALT+4    Pick any recent log with fzf, open in browser with color
  ALT+L    Insert last log filename at cursor (repeat to cycle older logs)

VIEWING LOGS
  open-last-log [-r] [-e] [-p PID]     Open previous command's log
  open-current-log [-r] [-e] [-p PID]  Open most recent command's log
  open-log                             Pick a log interactively with fzf
  open-url                             Find URLs in recent logs, pick with fzf, open in browser
  cat-last-log                         Print previous command's log to stdout
  cat-last-log-content                 Same, but strip the command-line header
  select-log [-r] [-e]                 Print a log filename chosen via fzf

FINDING LOG FILES
  history [-r] [-e] [-n N] [-p PID]    Print recent log filenames (up to 10)
  current-log [-r] [-e] [-p PID]       Print filename of the most recent log
  last-log [-r] [-e] [-p PID]          Print filename of the second most recent log
  all-commands [-r] [-e] [-n DAYS] [-c] [-l]
                                       List all logs with their command lines

  Flags for history / current-log / last-log:
    -r        RAW log filename (with ANSI codes) instead of SAN (stripped)
    -e        ENV log filename (metadata) instead of SAN
    -n N      Nth most recent log only (1 = most recent)
    -p PID    Use a specific zenlog session PID

  Flags for all-commands:
    -n DAYS   Limit to logs within the last N days (default: 30)
    -c        Current session only
    -l        Print filenames only, no command lines

MAINTENANCE
  purge-log -p DAYS [-y] [-P] [-b]     Delete logs older than DAYS days
    -p DAYS   (required) age threshold in days
    -y        Skip confirmation prompt
    -P        Dry run: print files that would be deleted
    -b        Run in the background
  du [OPTIONS]                         Show disk usage of the log directory
  free-space                           Print free bytes on the log filesystem
  update                               Download and build the latest zenlog

SESSION
  pids                                 List all active zenlog session PIDs
  in-zenlog                            Exit 0 if inside a zenlog session, 1 otherwise
  flush                                Flush log buffers for the current session
  flush-all                            Flush log buffers for all sessions

SHELL SETUP
  init                                 Interactive setup (recommended)
  basic-bash-setup                     Print Bash setup snippet (source into .bashrc)
  basic-zsh-setup                      Print Zsh setup snippet (source into .zshrc)

EXAMPLES
  # Open the previous command's output in less:
  zenlog open-last-log

  # Print the filename of the most recent log (useful in scripts):
  zenlog current-log

  # Find and open a URL from recent output:
  zenlog open-url

  # List all commands run in the last 7 days:
  zenlog all-commands -n 7

  # Delete logs older than 30 days without prompting:
  zenlog purge-log -p 30 -y

  # Show disk usage of the log directory:
  zenlog du -sh

LOG DIRECTORY (~/$ZENLOG_DIR, default ~/zenlog/)
  SAN/         Sanitized output (ANSI stripped) — grep-friendly
  RAW/         Raw output (with ANSI color codes)
  ENV/         Metadata: pwd, git branch, exit status, timestamps
  cmds/CMD/    Per-command logs; S/SS/… symlinks to most recent N outputs
  pids/PID/    Per-session logs (scoped to one shell)
  tags/TAG/    Per-tag logs (from inline # comments in commands)
  S, SS, …     Global most-recent sanitized logs (across all shells)
  R, RR, …     Global most-recent raw logs
  E, EE, …     Global most-recent env logs

See https://github.com/omakoto/zenlog for full documentation.

EOF
